document.title: [Archdiocese of Milwaukee Curriculum Documents, Kindergarten Science (Exit Expectations)]

69AC074C572A4DB4954C80E4C1F15479.description:
Explain that God created the world and I can do my
part to take care of it.

71426539836041A7A7BF7D021A591F0A.description:
Work cooperatively and respectfully with my
classmates.

7A83039D14524FEB81DEA1C823E3FC0D.description:
Give examples of ways humans can impact the
environment in positive ways.

E1C7FAE823A8434193A53BD39613BD8A.description:
Relate how human choices impact the environment
(example could be cutting trees for paper)

D6DF6CDCCC6B4961918FBF622D096801.description:
Things that people do to live comfortably can
affect the world around them. But they can make
choices that reduce their impacts on the land,
water, air, and other living things.

21EAA7C44A5A43048770C4C9775F5DD3.description:
Communicate solutions that will reduce the
impact of humans on the land, water, air, and/or
other living things in the local environment.
Recognize and responds to differences in the
environment (WMELS C.EL.1)

4003C409E8854ADCB5D92C03A313B601.description: Explain the importance of a weather scientist

437DBF60D82F4339B30DC73A9C9EE1BF.description:
Understand that not all severe weather happens in
our region

E87B96EDC4844597AFF0DC5B6C7187FC.description:
Describe the local severe weather (some ideas may
include tornado, blizzard, flood, thunderstorm, heat
and wind chill advisories)

9196F6876F494683B0E9A8953A505D00.description:
Weather scientists forecast severe weather so
that the communities can prepare for and
respond to these events.

C9196F5266E7422D8A28960932170402.description:
Some kinds of severe weather are more likely
than others in a given region.

C6039C4E2F8540619665361BE1A8C565.description:
Ask questions to obtain information about
the purpose of weather forecasting to prepare for,
and respond to, severe weather.
Can be addressed in conjunction with K-ESS2-1.   Ask simple scientific questions and draw conclusions
based on previous experiences.(WMELS C.EL.3)

B1329FB7338D44C9863EC9DC65F195B5.description:
Classify different objects (including food) used daily
and state what natural resource they come from.

91A52B00140E41ADB3C0508788A20894.description:
View a model and explain how the environment
helps an animal meet its needs.

FD909C47AC9649E582C95C72C2A3312A.description: Explain how animals live where their needs are met

27B58A6A0AB7477C8039D972EC7BAC1F.description:
Humans use natural resources for everything
they do.

78661E5F3C824BA48EC98B46C6A89A10.description:
Living things need water, air, and resources from
the land, and they live in places that have the
things they need.

7ED39D8C36E6464D9C4EAAFD7C38F4DC.description:
Use a model to represent the relationship
between the needs of different plants or animals
(including humans) and the places they live.
Can be addressed in conjunction with K-LS1.1 and KESS2-
2.   Ask simple scientific questions and draw conclusions
based on previous experiences.(WMELS C.EL.3)

03206EB602DD477A8BCCF28A558EB40A.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth and Human Activity

6CB2BA73846C470392E3635B23BD5D36.description: Relate how my choices impact the environment

34178F5E6DF74BB49AF1C0DF662ED7B5.description:
List how animals in different habitats change their
environment  (Note: examples could include squirrels digging,
woodpeckers pecking holes, weeds overtaking, trees
roots can break concrete, taller plants blocking sunlight
and growth below)

7196FF0239844567A0BEAFC27BCDA052.description:
Things that people do to live comfortably can
affect the world around them.

DD00804D998F485FAE9BDD78113A6D45.description:
Plants and animals can change their
environment.

189B2CA715D044A29ACBBDC6691E6892.description:
Construct an argument supported by
evidence for how plants and animals (including
humans) can change the environment to meet their
needs.
Show awareness of differences in their environment
(WMELS C.EL.1)

3A2EBEC5EFF44E298EDB91A83595E067.description:
Identify the impact of wind including strength and
direction

7016341D37C74B1BAD2EDF6825FA4B61.description:
Draw conclusions of weather conditions dependent
on seasons.

E86A53A17500446C896E204B99AB8D9E.description:
Measure weather conditions using a thermometer
and other tools

F94C635397D7471CB593148BAE6C5001.description:
Describe weather using the four conditions
(wind, temperature, precipitation, cloud coverage)

67FFB47C27B446D2A61BF397E6039142.description:
Discover that wind is moving air and has strength
and direction

9387A4A4B7DA4786A66F2BCF21A989C9.description:
People measure these conditions to describe and
record the weather and to notice patterns over
time.

46C4F5B299794A81BC5B5F4890854A06.description:
Weather is the combination of sunlight, wind,
snow or rain, and temperature in a particular
region at a particular time.

24F8CC02AD6645DE92B1571E5F87CC6F.description:
Use and share observations of local
weather conditions to describe patterns over time.
Purposefully seeks information through observation
to satisfy curiosity or need for answers (WMELS
C.EL.1)

0FE5FAAD6BF542B794899860A8509E3E.description: EARTH AND SPACE SCIENCES: Earth’s Systems

3C31962AD68A4FAFB9912006C9228562.description:
Work cooperatively and respectfully with
my classmates.

41C0893CFC94400C8ED67F1902908EB6.description:
Compare and contrast the needs of
animals and plants.

F9D8F3967D894A78B7B3AB9AE5D07D2B.description:
List that plants need sunlight, water and
nutrients

0A08CDA10E334002864D08540F18DDFC.description:
List that animals need food, water and
protection for growth.

882A8510830C4D628AA526A7A44CD8F3.description:
Plants need water and light to live and
grow.

7A9DE84236FC4481BBAB34E071722DC7.description:
Animals (including humans) obtain their
food from other plants or animals.

62F4E9BC1D6D496EB5A40FD8B09E1DA7.description:
All animals (including humans) need food
in order to live and grow.

5D7146FF9C5F4876A2AE5101A8C0008C.description:
Use observation to describe
patterns of what plants and animals
(including humans) need to survive.
Make reasonable explanations, using data
gathered from observations and
experiments. (WMELS C.EL.4)
[Clarification Statement: Examples of
patterns could include that animals need to
take in food but plants do not; the different
kinds of food needed by different types of
animals; the requirement of plants to have
light; and, that all living things need water.]

31B1C5DBA8534DD38CB0EC04B786E16A.description: LIFE SCIENCE: From Molecules to Organisms: Structures and Processes

6F82103CC34548738095957B27739D9D.description: Follow a plan to make a model.

1EEFF078E4A040C98184B0D6B1C844D5.description:
Plan how to make a model that blocks
sun heat.
(models may be similar to canopies, tents,
umbrellas, etc.)

054FFBF177AE4F0ABB883EFD807E3AAF.description:
Use tools and materials to design and
build a structure that will reduce the warming
effect of sunlight on an area.
Makes plans for testing hypotheses to prove or
disprove predictions. (WMELS C.EL.3)

0894FCA1541C4AA0AAD8B5A6DD0D6021.description:
Name different Earth surfaces (soil, sand,
water, rocks, etc.)

4E2AC85F246F4CDC8A1A8C0C9C4DC649.description:
Observe that the sun can warm the
Earth.

CB7DE880DAEA4A9283CBAA67FF8F3BD4.description: Identify the sun as a supplier of heat.

B7920B6B8BA7401CA79804C419203A0D.description: Explore that the Sun supplies heat to Earth.

46F1AE5C846041B6AA040EEC643C32B9.description:
Make observations to determine the
effect of sunlight on Earth’s surface.
Discriminates properties of nature, using a
variety of senses. (WMELS C.EL.1)

D292ADCDA3184050BE724D17EB8DC6BD.description:
Measure the effects of different
directions of pushes and pulls.

9A9B5813A3B44B95AAA4A76658A6C524.description:
Observe the effects of different strengths
of pushes and pulls.

4DA6195ABF6A4D76BF0B5DDDC1025C98.description:
Work cooperatively and respectfully with
my classmates.

144A9FCE343643758DFE45B4411A1243.description:
Measure how different pushes and pulls
change the motion of an object.

66A517319AC24DC9A9496B1E4C8403DE.description: Change the direction of pushes and pulls.

79E8F82C94884CA3B61F21832E1264B7.description: Change the strength of pushes and pulls.

D45332DBEF794D91B399BC1717DCF0F6.description:
Examples of pushes or pulls could include a string
attached to an object being pulled, a person pushing an
object, a person stopping a rolling ball, and two objects
colliding and pushing on each other.

929D47AF05F24B9C98A47C03D805294D.description:
Pushing or pulling on an object can change the speed or
direction of its motion and can start or stop it.

ABC65913CBC2438CA89F2C69C9445D4D.description:
Pushes and pulls can have different strengths and
directions.

EA314C2C9F344C5AACAB8847A5B845E3.description:
Plan and conduct an investigation to
compare the effects of different strengths or
different directions of pushes and pulls on the
motion of an object.
Engages in behavior to investigate consequences;
notices cause and effect relationships in daily
environment. (WMELS C.EL. 2)

D3E4BB4597E84674AD9467F326E58EF3.description: PHYSICAL SCIENCE: Motion and Stability: Forces and Interactions
